---
// /details/history — chapter page: how the payback math actually works, in
// plain English. Facts trace to product/payback_math.md (the canonical
// rulebook) and product_decisions.md ("Collectibles are not monetized").
// Keep this page in step with the spec if the rules change.
import DetailLayout from '@/layouts/DetailLayout.astro';
import { SITE } from '@/data/site';

export const prerender = true;

const title = `The history | ${SITE.name}`;
const description =
  'How Lanyard values a visit. Conservative gate prices, honest Park Hopper math, perk savings that never get repriced, and why collectibles never get a dollar amount.';
---
<DetailLayout
  title={title}
  description={description}
  heroKicker="The details · The history"
  heroTitle="Every dollar has a receipt."
  heroSub="The whole app is anchored to one promise. Lanyard will tell you the true value of your pass. A promise like that can't run on vibes, so the payback number follows a written rulebook. This is that rulebook in plain English."
>
  <section class="chapter">
    <p class="chapter__kicker">The rulebook</p>
    <h2>One set of rules, applied everywhere</h2>
    <p>
      What a visit is worth, how a perk counts, what happens when you upgrade mid-year. All of it
      is defined once and applied everywhere, so the number on your pass means the same thing on
      day 4 and day 340, on the Home tab and in your history. If two screens ever disagreed, one
      of them would be a bug by definition. The <a href="/calculator">free web calculator</a> runs
      the same rules.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="chapter">
    <p class="chapter__kicker">Visit value</p>
    <h2>A day is worth what it would have cost at the gate</h2>
    <p>
      When you log a visit, Lanyard values that day at the real single-day gate price of the park
      you entered. Not a made-up number, the published price of the ticket you didn't have to
      buy. Water parks carry their own lower prices, flagship parks carry theirs, and a day with
      multiple parks is anchored to the most expensive park you actually walked into.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="chapter">
    <p class="chapter__kicker">Hopper days</p>
    <h2>Park Hopper and Park-to-Park, priced honestly</h2>
    <p>
      Visit a second park in the same day and Lanyard adds what the operators actually charge for
      that, the flat park-hopper increment on a single-day ticket. Not a second full ticket,
      because that's not what a hopper day costs at the gate. A third or fourth park doesn't add
      more, because no operator prices one. And re-entering the same park twice is one day, not
      two. The math mirrors the ticket you'd really have bought for the day you really had.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="chapter">
    <p class="chapter__kicker">The bias</p>
    <h2>Conservative on purpose</h2>
    <p>
      When a park publishes more than one single-day price, peak versus off-peak, Lanyard records
      the lower one. That bias always points the same direction. Your pass is worth at least this
      much. An app that flatters you with inflated value gets caught within a season, and a
      payback number you can't trust is worth nothing at all.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="chapter">
    <p class="chapter__kicker">Your day</p>
    <h2>The last word on a visit's value is yours</h2>
    <p>
      The defaults are careful, but they're defaults. You know what your day was actually worth.
      Maybe it was a peak-price Saturday. Maybe the visit was your kid's, on a ticket that costs
      less. Every visit's value can be edited, and once you set it, your number is the truth from
      then on. Lanyard's job is a defensible starting point, not an argument with your memory.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="chapter">
    <p class="chapter__kicker">Perk value</p>
    <h2>Perks are receipts, not estimates</h2>
    <p>
      Perk savings work differently from visits, and the difference matters. A visit's value is
      derived from gate prices. A perk's value is recorded at the moment you save it. Free
      parking logs the day's real parking rate. A discount asks what you actually saved.
    </p>
    <p>
      And history never gets repriced. If parking goes from $35 to $40 next year, your old
      redemptions stay at $35, because that's what you actually saved on the day you saved it.
      Your history is a record of what happened, not a spreadsheet that drifts.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="chapter">
    <p class="chapter__kicker">Collectibles</p>
    <h2>Collectibles never get a dollar amount</h2>
    <p>
      The passholder magnet, the button, the lanyard. Lanyard tracks that you claimed them and
      refuses to price them, on purpose. Collectibles aren't rational. We want them, we wait in
      line for them, and we don't care what they're worth, because they're ours. Assigning $4.50
      of "value" to a magnet would miss the entire point of the magnet.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="chapter">
    <p class="chapter__kicker">The share</p>
    <h2>Built to be shown</h2>
    <p>
      Your payback card shares as a proper receipt, a rendered image with the story attached, my
      pass is 81% paid back. It exists because that's how passholders talk, one phone held up to
      another in a queue line. The receipt is the brag, and every number on it traces back to the
      rules on this page.
    </p>
    <p>
      <a href="/details">&larr; Back to the details</a>
    </p>
  </section>
</DetailLayout>
